PREAMBLE

This document is the controlling agreement for the use of the material
covered by it, as it is considered to be the contract signed between the
publisher and the beneficiary — as each contract has its own rules and
conditions. We see that monopolistic agreements not only restrict the
beneficiary but affect the value of intellectual work, turning it from a
light into a mere commodity, where the intellectual property right is
owned by the first intellectual depositor. Our vision for this property is
limited to the moral form of the intellectual work itself in accordance
with the rules below, unlike the monopoly licenses that place unfair
restrictions that keep the second party weak and encouraged to violate
them as much as possible.

We have a different vision: we offer our work (like computer software) to
please Allah, and this is the pillar of this license which distinguishes
it from proprietary licenses. Any other intention (like spreading knowledge
or getting profits) should be accomplished in ways that do not go against
our primary moral aim.

According to our beliefs (which we don't enforce on anyone, and you may or
may not share with us) that Islam certainly forbids monopoly and concealing
knowledge in general, and this comes from:

1.  The sound Hadith (saying of prophet Muhammad PBUH): "Who conceal any
    type of knowledge will be bridle with a bridle of fire on the Day of
    Resurrection." [1]

2.  Islamic Jurisprudence has specified what can be owned, and the rules
    do not apply to ideas as it is not a bounded tangible object. Almost
    all the terms of proprietary agreements fall under the ruling of
    forbidden Gharar [2] (a kind of fraud that uses uncertainty to fool
    customers) as described in Imam Muslim Sahih {and below that term we
    classify so many actions like selling negligible objects or unknowns
    or what can't be delivered or things that are not fully owned by the
    seller}. Such view is also shared by the four major scholars.

3.  The laws of Fiqh (Islamic Jurisprudence) have been perfected in the
    good centuries and no new rulings are allowed to be brought except
    for newly discovered things. This does not apply to ideas as they did
    exist in the past centuries and Muslims massively spread them without
    owning them. (Note: Almost all the Islamic literature is freely
    available on the internet.)

4.  Concealing useful knowledge from those who need it imposes damage on
    people for temporal gains to few individuals. This cannot be
    justified by Shari'a (Islamic Law) as there should be no harm nor
    malice.

5.  Even bringing interests to software publishers is not a valid excuse,
    because there are companies that produce and publish software without
    owning them (proprietary software) and yet gain profits.

6.  The so-called "Intellectual Property" is all about giving owners the
    right to forbid what Allah had made lawful in order to gain money,
    not by providing service nor goods. For the "owned" product is of
    uncertain and intangible nature and claiming its ownership opens the
    door for extortion.

We in Waqf (as in many anti-monopoly licenses) are concerned with the
interest of the general public over its counterpart of those who glorify
self-interest. We do not lose sight of the holder's interest in the reward
of Allah Almighty. We believe that the copyright and distribution are
"granted" and not "reserved" as stated in the terms below. We stop here
to clarify two points:

First: The favor and ethical rights of the holder are preserved and
acknowledged.

Second: The original author and any other party have the right to get
fees for enhancing the work, developing it, or providing paid
services or paid courses, etc. — but not for the work in its
intangible form. There is no contradiction between getting fees
for services because what is covered by "Waqf" is the source
form of the work, not the media nor the service. (In the same
way one can take fees on shipping fruits from a charitable Waqf
fruit field, or make juice from it.)

